You’re very close. I would not do a broad rewrite of SIGNING-SPEC.md, but I would make a small patch to TEST-SIGNING-SPEC.md before implementing the full suite.

My verdict:
 • SIGNING-SPEC.md is stable enough to start building the test harness and most of the suite.
 • TEST-SIGNING-SPEC.md is already strong, but it still has a few important blind spots and a couple of places where it can accidentally test the wrong thing.
 • The existing open issues in SIGNING-SPEC-PROBLEMS.md are not blockers for starting the tests.

So: patch the test spec first, then start implementation.

What I would change in TEST-SIGNING-SPEC.md first

1. Fix the client config-mismatch assertions

Right now the client-side mismatch tests compress two different surfaces into one.

SIGNING-SPEC.md distinguishes:
 • init reason = CONFIG_MISMATCH (§7.2.2)
 • request-time synthetic response = 503 { error: "CLIENT_INIT_FAILED" } (§11.4)

That means CG-3, AP-20, and AP-21 should explicitly say:
 • getInitState() may expose an init failure whose underlying reason is CONFIG_MISMATCH
 • mutating requests fail with synthetic 503 CLIENT_INIT_FAILED

Without that change, a correct implementation can fail those tests for the wrong reason.

2. Strengthen the fresh-session-probe / guest-suppression tests

CA-19, CA-20, DM-14, and AP-28 need to prove the request-time fresh probe from §7.4.2, not just the startup state determination from §7.4.3.

As written, those tests can pass even if the implementation only relies on startup session discovery.

I would change them so they:
 • start with the SW in "none"
 • change auth state after startup, without reload
 • issue the first mutating request
 • assert both:
 • the request used managed signing or deferred correctly
 • no guest wallet was created via getClientSignerAddress() === null

That second assertion is important. Right now some of those tests can pass even if the implementation incorrectly creates a suppressed guest wallet.

3. Add missing pre-signed passthrough exemption tests

The spec is explicit that pre-signed passthrough is exempt from some managed-signing checks:
 • maxBodySize enforcement exception in §5.4
 • content-encoding rejection only applies when the auth layer is signing (§5.5, §6.3)

The current suite does not test that.

Add tests for at least server mode:
 • pre-signed request with Content-Encoding: gzip passes through to sequencer
 • pre-signed oversized body is not rejected by the auth layer with 413

A client-mode counterpart is useful too, but server mode is the must-have.

4. Add the missing negative accept case

You test mandatory accept: */* injection when accept is in effectiveSignedHeaders (SA-10, SM-18, etc.), but not the inverse.

You should add:
 • server-mode test: when signedHeaders excludes accept, a request without Accept does not get accept: */* injected
 • client-mode test: same

Otherwise an implementation that always injects Accept could still go green.

5. Add link-endpoint malformed-request coverage

§7.9.2 step 3 explicitly calls out malformed JSON, missing fields, invalid base64, and invalid address format.

You already cover invalid JSON and non-EIP-55 address, but you should add:
 • invalid base64 keyMaterial → 400 INVALID_REQUEST
 • missing guestAddress → 400 INVALID_REQUEST
 • missing keyMaterial → 400 INVALID_REQUEST

Those are normative and currently uncovered.

6. Add link-protocol sequencing assertions

The linking protocol ordering is one of the most safety-critical parts of the whole spec (§7.9.2), but the suite mostly checks outcomes, not call sequence.

Using the controllable adapter call logs, add tests that verify:
 • deriveAddress happens before importWallet
 • assertAddressAvailable happens before importWallet
 • linkWallet happens after importWallet
 • on LINK_ADDRESS_MISMATCH, importWallet is not called
 • on ADDRESS_ALREADY_LINKED from assertAddressAvailable, importWallet is not called

This is one of the biggest remaining “comprehensive coverage” gaps.

7. Check Cache-Control: no-store on error responses too
The spec says responses from these endpoints must be no-store, not just success responses:
 • /_chopin-auth/session (§3.1)
 • /_chopin-auth/sign (§7.8)
 • /_chopin-auth/link (§7.9.1)

Your current tests mostly verify the 200 path. Extend them to assert no-store on 401/400 responses too.

8. Add auth-origin / dual coverage with no ClientSigner

The spec allows no client signer outside guest-only (§9.2, §10.1), but the current browser profiles almost always include one.

Add tests for:
 • auth-origin + clientSigner: "none" + valid managed session → managed signing works
 • auth-origin + clientSigner: "none" + no session → mutating request fails with 401 UNAUTHENTICATED
 • dual + clientSigner: "none" + managed session → middleware path still works

That closes a real configuration gap.

⸻

What I would add to SIGNING-SPEC-PROBLEMS.md

These do not require immediate changes to SIGNING-SPEC.md, but they are worth tracking so the test suite stays neutral.

New open issue: invalid allowedOrigins config handling is unspecified

§10.1 says entries must not include a trailing slash or path, but it does not say what the implementation must do if they do.

Why it matters:
 • the suite can test matching behavior
 • it cannot write a conformance test for invalid-config rejection without a defined failure surface

Recommendation:
 • track it as open
 • do not add conformance-core tests for invalid allowedOrigins entries yet

New open issue: mode/topology mismatch is normative, but rejection surface is unspecified

§2.3 says topology and server mode “MUST be paired,” but it does not define whether the client library, server library, or deployment tooling is responsible for detecting a mismatch.

Why it matters:
 • the suite can verify correct-pair behavior
 • it should not require runtime rejection of bad pairings unless the spec defines who must reject and how

Recommendation:
 • keep this out of conformance-core negative tests for now

New open issue: missing/non-JSON Content-Type behavior on /_chopin-auth/sign and /_chopin-auth/link is unspecified

The examples show Content-Type: application/json, but the normative text only says “parse JSON body.”

Why it matters:
 • the suite should not assert accept-vs-reject behavior for valid JSON bodies with missing or non-JSON Content-Type until the spec says so

Recommendation:
 • track it as open
 • keep those cases out of core tests

⸻

What does not need changing right now

I would leave SIGNING-SPEC.md alone for now on these:
 • session-probe timing window during guest creation
 • unknown-field behavior on /sign and /link
 • unexpected internal 5xx mapping during linking
 • IPv6 canonical-host behavior

Your current SIGNING-SPEC-PROBLEMS.md already handles those responsibly, and the test spec mostly avoids over-asserting them.

⸻

Can you start implementing after that patch?

Yes.

After those test-spec edits, I’d treat the suite as ready enough to implement in this order:
 1. Layer 0/1: vectors, harness, controllable adapters, mock sequencer
 2. Server mode + managed sign endpoint
 3. Guest-only client mode
 4. Auth-origin state machine
 5. Linking
 6. Dual mode
 7. Bridge protocol
 8. Fuzz / advisory / adapter-integration

Bottom line
 • Do not pause for a big spec rewrite.
 • Do make a focused patch to TEST-SIGNING-SPEC.md first.
 • Do add a few new open issues to SIGNING-SPEC-PROBLEMS.md.
 • After that, you can start implementing the tests with high confidence that the suite matches the current spec and will catch the most important failures.
